S.O.L.I.D PRINCIPLES:
- Implemented to keep my code clean, flexible, and easy to maintain as the project grows.
- SOLID refers to :
S - Single Responsibility Principle
O - Open/Close Principle
L - Liskov Substituton Principle
I - Interface Segregration Principle
D - Dependency Inversion Principle

Why SOLID Principles?
- Reduces the dependencies 
- makes design easier, understandable. 
- the system can be maintainable, testable, scalable, & reusable. 

Advantages: 
1. Highly Focussed Classes 
2. Plug and Play - Adding new features by writing new codes.
3. Unit Testing becomes easy - since classes are small and rely on interfaces.
4. No Surprise Bugs 
5. Fewer Merge Conflicts.

_____________________________________________________________________________
Principle     |     Focus     |          Result                               |
______________|_______________|_______________________________________________|
SRP           |    Classes    | Small, focused classes.                       |
OCP           |    Features   | Add new stuff without breaking old stuff.     |
LSP           |   Inheritance | Subclasses don't surprise the parent class.   |
ISP           |   Interfaces  | No "fat" interfaces with unused methods.      |
DIP           | Relationships | "Pluggable" architecture; easy to swap parts. |
______________|_______________|_______________________________________________|

1. S - Single Responsibility Principle
> A class should do one thing and do it well. 
> If a class has multiple responsibilities, they become "coupled" (glued together). 
> Changing one part accidentally breaks the others.

BAD PRACTICE: 
public class User {
    private String email;
    private String password;

    public User(String email, String password) {
        this.email = email;
        this.password = password;
    }

    // Responsibility 1: Validation Logic
    public boolean isValidEmail() {
        return email.contains("@");
    }

    // Responsibility 2: Database Persistence
    public void saveToDatabase() {
        System.out.println("Connecting to MySQL...");
        System.out.println("Inserting user into 'users' table...");
    }
}

GOOD PRACTICE: 
1. The Model (Data):
public class User {
    private String email;
    private String password;

    public User(String email, String password) {
        this.email = email;
        this.password = password;
    }
    // Getters and Setters only...
}

2. The service (Validator):
public class UserValidator {
    public boolean validate(User user) {
        return user.getEmail().contains("@");
    }
}

3. Repository (Database Guy):
public class UserRepository {
    public void save(User user) {
        System.out.println("Saving to database via JDBC/Hibernate...");
    }
}

2. O - Open/Close Principle
> Stop the "Switch-Case" or "If-Else" nightmare. 
> Instead of changing the "Engine" of your app to add a new "Part," 
> Design the engine to accept "Plug-ins."
______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
> You should be able to add new features to your app without touching the code you’ve already written and tested. 
> If you have to open up an existing, working class to add an if statement every time a new requirement comes in, you’re breaking OCP.

BAD PRACTICE:
public class InsurancePremiumCalculator {
    public double calculatePremium(Object client) {
        if (client instanceof HealthClient) {
            return 100.0; 
        } else if (client instanceof HomeClient) {
            return 250.0;
        }
        // Problem: If we add 'CarInsurance', we MUST modify this class.
        // This risks breaking the existing Health/Home logic!
        return 0;
    }
}

GOOD PRACTICE:
1. Interface (The Plug):
public interface InsurancePolicy {
    double calculate();
}

2. Implementation (Plug-ins):
public class HealthPolicy implements InsurancePolicy {
    public double calculate() { return 100.0; }
}

public class HomePolicy implements InsurancePolicy {
    public double calculate() { return 250.0; }
}

// NEW FEATURE: Just add a new class! No need to touch existing code.
public class CarPolicy implements InsurancePolicy {
    public double calculate() { return 150.0; }
}

3. Calculator (Closed for Modification):
public class InsurancePremiumCalculator {
    public double calculatePremium(InsurancePolicy policy) {
        // This code NEVER changes again, no matter how many 
        // new insurance types we add in the future.
        return policy.calculate();
    }
}

3. L - Liskov Substituton Principle
> A subclass should be able to replace its parent class without breaking the program.
> Inheritance should represent a true "is-a" relationship in terms of behavior, not just attributes. 
> If a subclass overrides a method from the parent only to throw an "UnsupportedOperationException," that's a red flag!

BAD PRACTICE: 
The LSP Violation: 
public class Rectangle {
    protected int width, height;

    public void setWidth(int width) { this.width = width; }
    public void setHeight(int height) { this.height = height; }
    public int getArea() { return width * height; }
}

public class Square extends Rectangle {
    @Override
    public void setWidth(int width) {
        this.width = width;
        this.height = width; // Forced to keep sides equal
    }

    @Override
    public void setHeight(int height) {
        this.height = height;
        this.width = height; // Forced to keep sides equal
    }
}

GOOD PRACTICE:
The Behavioural Fix:
public interface Shape {
    int getArea();
}

public class Rectangle implements Shape {
    private int width, height;
    public Rectangle(int w, int h) { this.width = w; this.height = h; }
    public int getArea() { return width * height; }
}

public class Square implements Shape {
    private int side;
    public Square(int side) { this.side = side; }
    public int getArea() { return side * side; }
}

4. I - Interface Segregration Principle:
> This principle is all about keeping your Java Interfaces lean and mean.
> Clients should not be forced to depend on methods they do not use.
> Don't create a "Master Interface" that has 20 methods if some of your classes only need two of them. 
> If you force a class to implement a method it doesn't need (usually leaving it empty or throwing an error), you’ve created a "Fat Interface."
> It’s better to have many specific interfaces than one general-purpose interface. 
> This keeps your classes lightweight and prevents them from having an "identity crisis."
BAD PRACTICE:
1. The Fat Interface:
public interface SmartDevice {
    void print();
    void scan();
    void fax();
}

// Problem: An old-school printer doesn't know how to fax or scan!
public class OldPrinter implements SmartDevice {
    public void print() {
        System.out.println("Printing document...");
    }

    public void scan() {
        // I don't know how to scan! 
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException(); 
    }

    public void fax() {
        // I don't know how to fax!
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException();
    }
}

GOOD PRACTICE:
1. The Segregrated way:
public interface Printer {
    void print();
}

public interface Scanner {
    void scan();
}

public interface Fax {
    void fax();
}

// Now, the Old Printer only does what it's supposed to:
public class OldPrinter implements Printer {
    public void print() {
        System.out.println("Printing...");
    }
}

// And the high-end office machine can do everything by implementing multiple interfaces:
public class SuperMachine implements Printer, Scanner, Fax {
    public void print() { /* ... */ }
    public void scan() { /* ... */ }
    public void fax() { /* ... */ }
}

5. D - Dependency Inversion Principle:
> High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. 
> Both should depend on abstractions.
> Abstractions should not depend on details. Details should depend on abstractions.
> Depend on interfaces, not concrete classes.

BAD PRACTICE:
1. The Hard Wired Way: 
public class EmailProvider {
    public void sendEmail(String message) {
        System.out.println("Sending Email: " + message);
    }
}

public class NotificationService {
    // Problem: High-level class depends on a CONCRETE low-level class.
    private EmailProvider emailProvider = new EmailProvider();

    public void notify(String message) {
        emailProvider.sendEmail(message);
    }
}

GOOD PRACTICE:
1. The Inverted Way: 
a. The Abstraction:
public interface MessageSender {
    void send(String message);
}

b. The Details (Low level Implementation):
public class EmailProvider implements MessageSender {
    public void send(String message) { System.out.println("Email: " + message); }
}

public class SmsProvider implements MessageSender {
    public void send(String message) { System.out.println("SMS: " + message); }
}

c. The High Level Module (Decoupled):
public class NotificationService {
    private MessageSender sender;

    // Dependency Injection: We "inject" the tool via the constructor
    public NotificationService(MessageSender sender) {
        this.sender = sender;
    }

    public void notify(String message) {
        sender.send(message);
    }
}

